---
import VizPlaceholder from '../../VizPlaceholder.astro';
---

<section
  id="memory"
  class="border-y border-neutral-900 bg-neutral-900/40 px-6 py-20 md:py-28"
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <h2
        class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-4xl"
      >
        The knowledge dissolves with the session
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
        There is a second shift hiding inside the first. Work used to be one
        person per problem; now it is <mark>you plus a handful of agents</mark>,
        and the agents hold the implementation details. You operate like an
        architect: you care that the data flows through the system the right
        way, you do not sit at the keyboard of every change. The agent holds
        those details, the way a coworker used to.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
        Every company knows how that story ends. The coworker who knows why the
        payment retry logic looks the way it does changes jobs, and the
        knowledge leaves with them, because it was never written down. With
        agents, that does not happen once a year. It happens every time a
        session ends.
      </p>
    </div>

    <figure
      class="mx-auto mt-14 max-w-4xl border-y border-neutral-800 py-10 text-center"
    >
      <p class="text-2xl font-medium leading-snug text-neutral-100 sm:text-3xl">
        Agents are developers who <span class="text-accent"
          >leave after every single task</span
        >.
      </p>
    </figure>

    <div class="mt-14 grid items-center gap-12 lg:grid-cols-2">
      <div class="space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
        <p>
          Play out a single day. In the morning you work on the frontend repo
          with an agent: a tricky fix, real reasoning about why this approach
          and not the other. The session ends, and that reasoning dissolves. In
          the afternoon you move to the backend repo, another session, more
          decisions. It dissolves too.
        </p>
        <p>
          Just you, one day, two repos, and the why behind both changes is
          already out of reach. The session logs exist, but they are files on
          your machine that nothing ever reads back.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <VizPlaceholder
          label="SessionDissolve island: you + agent on frontend cube, session fades out; then backend cube, fades again"
          ratio="aspect-[16/10]"
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
